Super Mart Sales Analytics & Forecasting

Power BI • DAX • Power Query • Time Intelligence • Forecasting

2 Dashboards

▼

Problem Statement: Comprehensive analytics solution for a retail company to analyze historical sales performance, identify revenue patterns, and forecast future trends for proactive inventory management and strategic planning.

Dashboard 1: Sales Performance Analysis

Key Metrics: 1.6M Sales | 22K Orders | 175K Profit

  • Built multi-dimensional sales dashboard analyzing payment modes, regions, segments, and product categories using DAX formulas
  • Created time-series visualizations tracking monthly sales and profit trends, revealing seasonal spike in November-December
  • Identified West region as top performer (33% of total sales) and Consumer segment as primary revenue driver (48%)

Dashboard 2: Predictive Sales Forecasting

3 Years Historical Data | 15-Day Forecast | 10 State Analysis

  • Implemented Power BI's exponential smoothing algorithm to forecast 15-day sales trends with confidence intervals
  • Analyzed 3 years of historical data (2019-2021) to identify seasonal patterns and growth trends
  • Built state-level performance breakdown identifying California as leading market (0.34M in sales)

Key Insights: Project demonstrates end-to-end analytics from descriptive analysis to predictive modeling, combining historical performance tracking with forward-looking forecasts to enable strategic business decisions.

NovaCare Hospital Analytics Dashboard

Power BI • Excel • DAX

1 Dashboard

▼

Problem Statement: Analyze hospital operations data to understand patient workflow, bed occupancy patterns, billing efficiency, and doctor performance to optimize resource allocation and improve healthcare delivery at NovaCare Hospitals.

Work and Leads Workflow Dashboard

Key Metrics: ₹190.43M Billing | 3.8K Private Beds | 8 Diagnosis Types

  • Patient Workflow Analysis: Tracked admission (05-Dec-22), discharge (12-Jan-23), and follow-up dates (15-Jan-23) to monitor patient journey and length of stay
  • Bed Occupancy Optimization: Analyzed bed utilization showing Private beds at 3.8K occupancy, General at 2.3K, and ICU at 1.5K - identified opportunity to optimize ICU capacity
  • Doctor Performance Tracking: Created feedback volume analysis across 7 doctors with Tejas Saxena and Jay Sinha leading at 1.02K feedback each, enabling performance evaluation
  • Disease Pattern Recognition: Diagnosed Viral Infection as top condition (2.00K cases, 14.3%), followed by Flu (1.72K) and Malaria (1.43K) to guide resource planning
  • Billing & Insurance Analysis: Analyzed billing vs health insurance coverage showing CT Scan generated ₹63M (highest), followed by Ultrasound (₹58M) and MRI (₹53M), with insurance coverage declining from ₹57M to ₹5M across tests
  • Revenue by Diagnostic Service: Identified X-Ray and Blood Test as low revenue generators (₹5M, ₹11M) despite high volume, suggesting pricing review opportunity

Key Insights: Private bed occupancy dominates at 50% of total capacity. CT Scans drive highest revenue but show significant insurance coverage gaps. Viral infections represent 14.3% of all diagnoses, indicating potential for preventive care programs. Doctor feedback distribution is balanced, suggesting equitable patient load management.

HR Analytics Dashboard

Tableau • Excel • Data Visualization

2 Dashboards

▼

Problem Statement: Analyze employee attrition patterns and workforce demographics to identify key factors driving employee turnover and provide actionable insights for HR retention strategies across departments, age groups, and education backgrounds.

Dashboard 1: HR Data Overview

Dataset: 1,470 Employees | 43 Fields | Multi-dimensional Analysis

  • Data Structure Analysis: Organized comprehensive HR dataset with 1,470 employee records across 43 attributes including attrition status, business travel frequency, age bands, department, and education field
  • Data Segmentation: Categorized employees by attrition label (Ex-Employees vs Current Employees), department (Sales, R&D), and CF age bands (25-34, 35-44, 45-54, Over 55)
  • Data Quality: Ensured clean dataset with proper categorization of business travel patterns (Travel_Frequently, Travel_Rarely) and education fields (Life Sciences, Medical, Other)

Dashboard 2: Attrition Analytics Dashboard

Key Metrics: 1,470 Employees | 237 Attrition | 16.12% Rate | 1,233 Active | Avg Age 37

  • Attrition Overview KPIs: Built executive summary showing 237 employees left (16.12% attrition rate) from total 1,470 workforce, with 1,233 active employees averaging 37 years of age
  • Department Analysis: Identified R&D as critical concern with 92 attritions (38.82% of total), followed by Sales with 12 (5.06%), enabling targeted retention strategies
  • Age Group Distribution: Discovered 25-34 age band has highest employee count (213) but also significant attrition, while Over 55 group shows lowest numbers (54 employees)
  • Gender Disparity: Revealed males have higher attrition (150) compared to females (87), with gender-based attrition rates varying significantly across age groups (Under 25: 29.11% female vs 15.61% male for 35-44)
  • Education Field Impact: Analyzed attrition by education showing Life Sciences (89), Medical (63), and Marketing (35) as top fields losing employees, indicating sector-specific challenges
  • Job Satisfaction Matrix: Created satisfaction ratings table showing Research Scientists (292 grand total) and Sales Executives (326) have highest representation, with detailed satisfaction levels (1-4 scale) by role
  • Interactive Filtering: Implemented Tableau filters enabling drill-down analysis by department, age group, gender, and education field for dynamic insights

Key Insights: R&D department faces critical retention challenge with 38.82% of all attrition. Male employees show 72% higher attrition than females. Life Sciences and Medical education backgrounds account for 64% of attrition, suggesting industry-specific factors. Age group 25-34 represents both highest workforce concentration and attrition risk. Job satisfaction varies significantly by role, with Research Scientists and Sales roles needing focused retention programs.
